SIMPLE: binomial
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Binomial
<hw>Bi*no"mi*al</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>bis</ets> twice + <ets>nomen</ets> name: cf. F. <ets>binome</ets>,
LL. <ets>binomius</ets> (or fr. <ets>bi-</ets> + Gr. <ets><?/</ets>
distribution ?). Cf. <er>Monomial</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>An
expression consisting of two terms connected by the sign plus (+) or
minus (-); as, <mathex>a + b</mathex>, or <mathex>7 -
3</mathex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Binomial</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Binomial
<hw>Bi*no"mi*al</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of two
terms; pertaining to binomials; <as>as, a <ex>binomial</ex>
root</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Nat. Hist.)</fld> <def>Having two names; -- used of
the system by which every animal and plant receives two names, the one
indicating the genus, the other the species, to which it
belongs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Binomial theorem</b></col> <fld>(Alg.)</fld>, <cd>the
theorem which expresses the law of formation of any power of a
binomial.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Binominal</ent>⟦br⟧
